Press Release


            Employers’ cost to provide employee benefits has risen 24% since 2001, Willis Towers Watson analysis finds
        

            Employers now spending more on health care benefits, less on retirement benefits
        


                July 18, 2017
            

| United States
                
            




















ARLINGTON, VA, July 18, 2017 — U.S. employers’ cost to provide employee benefits, measured as a percentage of pay, increased 24% between 2001 and 2015, fueled largely by a doubling in health care benefit costs, according to a new analysis by Willis Towers Watson (NASDAQ: WLTW), a leading global advisory, broking and solutions company. The analysis reveals a major shift in how employers allocate benefit dollars and prompts questions as to whether they are delivering the benefits their employees want. 
